    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Yes, there are mathematical flaws in waiting until the age of 70 to  collect on Social Security, instead of starting at 65 (Letters, June 18): Despite the much higher monthly payments for those who wait, it would take many years to recoup the lost amounts.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Yes, there are mathematical flaws in waiting until the age of 70 to  collect on Social Security, instead of starting at 65 (Letters, June 18): Despite the much higher monthly payments for those who wait, it would take many years to recoup the lost amounts.</p>
        <p>But there is another danger that has nothing to do with complex mathematics:</p>
        <p>If you die during that five-year wait, you will have collected nothing; and if you are single, no one else will, either.</p>
        <p>MARVIN NEWMAN  New Canaan, Conn., June 28</p>
      </block>
